Add Vulkan backend (parity with ROCm, target better perf)

STATUS: planned, not started.

GOAL
Add a third backend alongside Metal and ROCm targeting Vulkan compute, primarily for AMD Strix Halo (gfx1151, RDNA 3.5, wave32, UMA). Aim for feature parity with the ROCm backend (every wrapper in ds4_rocm.c) and try to beat its end-to-end token rate (current baseline ~39.9 prefill / 15.7 generation t/s on the IQ2_XXS+Q2_K chat-v2 build).

WHY THIS MIGHT WIN OVER ROCm ON gfx1151
- RADV often produces tighter wave32 code than HIP-clang on RDNA.
- Vulkan compute lets us pin subgroupSize=32 explicitly via VK_EXT_subgroup_size_control.
- Pre-recorded command buffers eliminate the per-launch overhead that ROCM_TIME_SCOPE measures.
- True zero-copy on UMA via host-visible+device-local memory (vs the partial hipHostRegister story documented in CLAUDE.md).
- llama.cpp's Vulkan backend already beats its ROCm backend on most RDNA consumer parts.
- Realistic DRAM ceiling is unchanged at ~188 GiB/s (see project_strix_halo_bw_ceiling); the win is in launch overhead, fusion freedom, and possibly better compiled code.

SCOPE
Match every wrapper currently exported by ds4_rocm.c (~55 wrappers, ~20 distinct kernels). Quant formats: Q8_0, Q4_K, IQ2_XXS, Q2_K, F16. Ops: matmul variants, RMS norm, head_rms_norm, RoPE, attention (incl. SWA-ring), attention_output_low_q8, FP8 KV pack/unpack, store_raw_kv, MoE routing, router_select, top-K (incl. parallel block-K), get_rows / set_rows, dsv4 norms, HC family (split sinkhorn / weighted sum / weighted_sum_norm), shared MoE.

DESIGN CHOICES (already proposed, defaults applied unless redirected)
- Shader language: GLSL compiled to SPIR-V via glslc.
- SPIR-V at build time, embedded as byte-array .h files (mirrors how the Metal .air bundle and the ROCm fatbin work).
- Use VMA (Vulkan Memory Allocator, vendored single-header) for buffer suballocation. Vulkan TUs have no "no C++" constraint (the CLAUDE.md rule was specific to ds4_rocm.c under hipcc).
- New build flag DS4_VULKAN=1 in the Makefile. Vulkan is opt-in initially; ROCm stays default on Linux.
- Backend ABI matches the ds4_metal_* shim convention so ds4.c's graph scheduler doesn't change.
- Add a DS4_BACKEND_VULKAN enum value and extend ds4_backend_is_graph() if we want pre-recorded command buffers gated by graph-mode (see ds4.c model_open call sites).

VALIDATION GATES (per CLAUDE.md)
1. DS4_VULKAN=1 make ds4 ds4_vulkan_kernel_test
2. ./ds4_vulkan_kernel_test ends with OK (mirror the 40-test ROCm harness; one STEP per kernel + edge cases + quant-format roundtrips).
3. Canonical decode: time ./ds4 --backend vulkan -p "Briefly explain what makes the AMD Strix Halo APU well-suited for running large language models on a single chip." -n 200 --temp 0 --seed 42 must produce a coherent multi-paragraph thinking-mode reply.
4. End-to-end t/s vs ROCm baseline (39.9 / 15.7). Target: >= ROCm; success-tier: >15%.

